00:21.460 --> 00:23.580
This has AIDS, it's from Africa.

00:24.260 --> 00:25.460
You're in shock.

00:25.540 --> 00:28.060
You've been injected with a
hypodermic possibly exposed to HIV.

00:28.260 --> 00:31.580
Now a woman and her baby
halfway across the world are at risk.

00:33.740 --> 00:35.020
Nobody knows that I quit.

00:35.220 --> 00:36.780
NORBAC would have been finished.

00:36.860 --> 00:38.980
We had a vaccine to design.
Where were you?

00:39.420 --> 00:40.780
You bailed on your own lab.

00:41.100 --> 00:42.700
We've compared the protein structure

00:42.860 --> 00:45.620
of your particular strain
with every available HIV drug.

00:45.980 --> 00:48.260
It's predicted to be
resistant to all of them.

00:48.860 --> 00:49.980
All of them?

00:50.140 --> 00:52.340
Kids ate a chicken poisoned with prions.

00:52.540 --> 00:54.220
Yeah, I remember that
whole mad cow disease scare.

00:54.340 --> 00:56.780
- I found I.Q. spikes.
- Where are you going next with this?

00:56.940 --> 00:58.820
Well, I've read about
a British neuroscientist

00:58.980 --> 01:00.940
who's been working with people
exposed to mad cow.

01:01.100 --> 01:04.860
Jack, we're trying to trace back
the strain before Sean to patient zero.

01:05.740 --> 01:08.380
David, we've been infecting
the cells in culture

01:08.500 --> 01:10.100
- with Audrey's HIV.
- Bob, what's the matter?

01:10.660 --> 01:13.700
I'm telling you she needs
to have her baby out right away.

01:14.260 --> 01:16.100
The baby's CD4 count.

01:17.860 --> 01:19.100
HIV.

03:14.820 --> 03:16.540
<i>- What?
- David.</i>

03:17.740 --> 03:20.540
Carlos, it's 3 o'clock
in the fucking morning. What's going on?

03:20.820 --> 03:22.100
<i>Let me in, David.</i>

03:22.220 --> 03:23.420
Are you all right?

03:24.380 --> 03:25.460
Carlos?

03:38.260 --> 03:41.780
So I just thought...
David, I was just all right.

03:42.180 --> 03:44.260
That's what happens when you drink.

03:46.700 --> 03:48.180
Talk to me.

03:53.700 --> 03:56.020
I need to...
I need to leave all this.

03:56.140 --> 03:58.300
- My job, NORBAC, Canada.
- Whoa, whoa, whoa,

03:58.580 --> 04:00.020
Carlos. What's going on?

04:00.140 --> 04:02.140
I have to go back to Africa, David.

04:02.340 --> 04:05.780
There are people dying there.
They need me.

04:06.380 --> 04:09.300
They needed doctors 4 years ago,
why'd you leave then?

04:11.100 --> 04:13.900
I couldn't breathe,
I had to get out.

04:14.260 --> 04:16.300
- I know the feeling.
- Okay, then you...

04:16.459 --> 04:19.100
you know the feeling of when
it's time to return.

04:19.339 --> 04:22.620
You left the lab
and now you came back,

04:22.740 --> 04:24.820
and I need to go back to Africa.

04:30.260 --> 04:32.140
What happened to you over there?

04:34.700 --> 04:36.740
Why couldn't you breathe, Carlos?

04:39.340 --> 04:41.020
I'm sorry.

04:41.540 --> 04:43.180
I'm sorry.

04:46.700 --> 04:48.300
I'm so sorry.

05:15.300 --> 05:17.100
No!

05:14.980 --> 05:17.500
2.03 - The Cocktail

05:26.420 --> 05:28.220
Want anything in it?

05:28.380 --> 05:29.500
Sorry?

05:29.900 --> 05:32.620
Coffee, do you want anything in it?
Sugar, honey,

05:32.740 --> 05:34.180
hair of the dog?

05:34.860 --> 05:36.580
Black, thank you.

05:40.020 --> 05:41.820
I can't let you go, Carlos.

05:41.940 --> 05:43.420
Not right now, okay?

05:43.620 --> 05:45.940
We get through this, we'll talk,
and I promise you,

05:46.060 --> 05:48.740
whatever you decide is best for yourself,
I will get behind it.

05:49.900 --> 05:52.140
Do you have any clam juice?

05:53.300 --> 05:54.620
Doesn't everybody?

05:56.500 --> 05:58.340
And baking soda,

05:58.500 --> 06:01.020
and bitters, and aspirin, please.

06:19.940 --> 06:21.780
I thought you didn't get hangovers.

06:21.900 --> 06:23.260
When I do, I do.

06:23.340 --> 06:24.660
That thing really work?

06:27.340 --> 06:30.100
My father's recipe. It clears the head,

06:30.260 --> 06:32.940
dulls the pain, good for indigestion.

06:34.660 --> 06:36.580
I'll ve to try it sometime.

06:37.300 --> 06:39.380
Clam juice with baking soda...

06:42.180 --> 06:43.820
bitters and aspirin.

06:45.980 --> 06:47.300
What?

06:48.380 --> 06:50.140
Your father's a fucking genius.

06:50.460 --> 06:52.420
Drink up.
We got a lot of work to do.

06:54.020 --> 06:56.060
Well, we tried every HIV
drug on the planet.

06:56.180 --> 06:58.900
Yes, but we haven't tried
every drug on the planet.

06:59.140 --> 07:01.300
You think you can stop
HIV with aspirin?

07:01.420 --> 07:02.460
Maybe, maybe.

07:02.620 --> 07:05.660
There are many drugs made to solve one
problem later discovered to solve another.

07:05.860 --> 07:08.580
Right, so we take
our most promising HIV cocktail,

07:08.700 --> 07:11.860
the one with Tenofovir and Viracept,
and we add Viagra to it.

07:12.020 --> 07:14.860
We add Tylenol, we add epilepsy meds,
we add everything.

07:15.140 --> 07:17.140
David, there are like 10,000 drugs

07:17.220 --> 07:19.460
out there, including
behind and over the counter.

07:19.500 --> 07:20.700
Yeah, what's your point?

07:21.300 --> 07:23.740
Well, one,
to get this done in 2 days,

07:23.860 --> 07:26.420
- we don't have the manpower.
- We don't have enough Petri dishes.

07:26.540 --> 07:29.060
And 2, we can't possibly get that
many drugs here by this afternoon.

07:29.300 --> 07:31.460
Then we get as many
as humanly possible.

07:31.660 --> 07:33.220
- It's crazy.
- Thank you.

07:33.980 --> 07:36.220
I'll contact as many labs as I can.

07:36.780 --> 07:37.660
What?

07:38.140 --> 07:39.580
- What?
- What?

07:42.140 --> 07:44.260
Well, would it be logical to start

07:44.420 --> 07:47.740
with the anti-inflammatories
to curb the element of HIV? No?

07:47.860 --> 07:51.340
Viagra was made for angina, right?
It turns out it gave men big woodies.

07:51.460 --> 07:54.740
Now, is there a connection between
angina and big woodies? I don't think so.

07:54.940 --> 07:55.820
So...

07:55.860 --> 07:58.300
So, logically we assume
that there is no logic.

07:58.420 --> 07:59.740
We try every drug.

08:02.620 --> 08:04.140
- It's still crazy.
- Yes it is.

08:04.260 --> 08:07.100
But you know what? Sometimes,
some pretty cool shit happens by accident,

08:07.220 --> 08:08.820
so  let's go look for an accident.

08:09.540 --> 08:11.260
What have we got to lose, right?

08:31.580 --> 08:32.460
Bob...

08:33.140 --> 08:36.220
- The baby will be HIV positive in 2 days.
- Two days?

08:36.380 --> 08:38.659
Yeah, if he follows the same
rate of infection as Audrey.

08:38.780 --> 08:41.419
I mean, he could go even sooner.
His immune system isn't fully developed.

08:41.659 --> 08:42.780
-  Wow.
- Yeah.

08:42.860 --> 08:45.500
David, this is a list of all the prescription

08:45.580 --> 08:47.380
and non-prescription drugs
we can get our hands on.

08:47.460 --> 08:49.180
Okay, thanks, Wes.
Bob, take a look at that.

08:49.260 --> 08:51.020
Which labs are helping us?

08:51.580 --> 08:53.260
All these labs
are available for help?

08:53.340 --> 08:55.060
They're clearing their plates.
Apparently we have some pull.

08:55.220 --> 08:58.060
Audrey Graves has pull.
They understand the time crunch?

08:58.260 --> 08:59.900
- I made it very clear.
- Bob.

09:01.060 --> 09:02.140
Mix and match

09:02.260 --> 09:05.500
with their most promising HIV cocktail
and divide the total by 16 labs,

09:05.620 --> 09:07.580
taking into consideration
each lab's manpower.

09:07.860 --> 09:08.980
Hold on.

09:09.060 --> 09:12.580
We get 5,081 combinations.
Aberhold-Shard gets 260,

09:12.700 --> 09:14.860
Ace Bioneer gets 300...

09:15.060 --> 09:16.380
- Bob.
- Hmm?

09:16.500 --> 09:18.260
Let's get the dish totals
to Wes ASAP,

09:18.340 --> 09:20.100
- and get to work on our own dishes.
- Sure.

09:27.140 --> 09:30.780
Looks like little Sam there has
mastered occlusion and perspective.

09:30.900 --> 09:32.660
Is that that unusual?

09:32.780 --> 09:34.340
Uh, he's seven.

09:35.100 --> 09:36.780
Oh, I love kid's art.

09:37.180 --> 09:38.660
Look at this one.

09:41.940 --> 09:43.620
Uh, can't figure it out.

09:43.900 --> 09:46.940
I think it's a ceiling fan.
He drew the parts disassembled.

09:47.700 --> 09:48.620
Wow.

09:48.820 --> 09:51.700
Hello, I'm principal Oakley.
You're the people from NORBAC.

09:51.820 --> 09:53.100
Yes, Mayko Tran.

09:53.260 --> 09:54.620
Hey, I'm Simon Jessup.

09:55.060 --> 09:57.220
I understand you may have
some good news for us.

09:57.340 --> 09:59.900
We hope so.
We have evidence that 1 in 4 of the kids

10:00.060 --> 10:02.060
who ate the prion contaminated
chicken last year

10:02.220 --> 10:03.620
are showing dramatic spikes in I.Q.

10:04.300 --> 10:07.020
- You mean they may actually be better off?
- Well...

10:07.180 --> 10:09.820
- We'll know more when we've done a few tests.
- Of course.

10:10.340 --> 10:11.700
If there's anything you need...

10:11.820 --> 10:14.460
Just a few bouncing bundles of joy.

10:15.460 --> 10:18.420
There's something just
as important as finding the right cocktail.

10:18.500 --> 10:20.380
- What?
- Getting it to Africa in time

10:20.500 --> 10:21.980
to put the
brakes on this strain.

10:22.100 --> 10:24.500
It'll take years for it to get
through all the regulatory hoops.

10:24.660 --> 10:26.260
Then I'll take it there myself.

10:26.340 --> 10:28.900
You really think the American drug
industry's gonna let this out in the world

10:28.980 --> 10:30.700
without American companies
profiting from it?

10:31.100 --> 10:34.540
You know, it's all going to be pointless
if we cannot find the origin of this strain.

10:34.660 --> 10:36.820
Nah, I'll tell you what.
You find patient zero,

10:36.900 --> 10:38.580
I'll find a way to get
the drugs to Africa.

10:38.780 --> 10:40.100
You got a deal.

10:42.940 --> 10:44.260
How's it going?

10:44.460 --> 10:46.580
- We're missing Galantamine.
- I ordered it, David.

10:46.740 --> 10:48.620
I know you want every drug.
I know I ordered it.

10:48.860 --> 10:50.220
I don't see it, Bob.

10:50.300 --> 10:52.060
I know the whole point of this experiment

10:52.140 --> 10:54.500
is that we try every drug
we can get, and Galantamine

10:54.620 --> 10:57.300
is in a class of
acetylcholinesterase inhibitors

10:57.420 --> 11:00.100
that we are going to use.
I know I ordered it.

11:00.220 --> 11:02.380
Bob, Bob, get somebody
down to this clinic, okay?

11:02.420 --> 11:04.580
- They'll have it, it'll be fine.
- Okay, David.

11:04.740 --> 11:06.980
No, I'll go myself.

11:07.220 --> 11:09.060
I'm sorry about the mix-up.

11:51.740 --> 11:54.820
There you go. I told you
your brain wouldn't explode, didn't I?

11:55.020 --> 11:57.900
Though a little bit did
melt out your ear.

12:00.180 --> 12:02.620
- You talk weird.
- Oh dear, shame.

12:03.740 --> 12:05.940
That's another one
we're gonna have to guillotine.

12:08.820 --> 12:10.820
You do have a way with kids.

12:11.100 --> 12:13.420
- A strange way, but...
- I love kids.

12:13.540 --> 12:15.780
I'm still one myself.
How many more do we have to see?

12:15.860 --> 12:17.980
Uh, about 30 more.

12:18.100 --> 12:19.460
I hate kids.

12:19.500 --> 12:22.020
I hope the next one
doesn't smell like frogs too.

12:24.260 --> 12:26.620
Hello, please come in.

12:49.060 --> 12:51.940
Ruby McGhee... Oh, there you are.

12:53.660 --> 12:56.620
Okay, Ruby, so this is kind of like a...

12:56.700 --> 12:59.260
a brain beauty contest,
all right?

12:59.420 --> 13:02.620
And the more flashy colours
that we see on our computer,

13:02.780 --> 13:04.020
the better.

13:04.380 --> 13:06.020
And it helps if you wear the magic hat.

13:06.180 --> 13:08.620
Electroencephalogram helmet.

13:11.100 --> 13:12.540
Right, yes.

13:13.660 --> 13:16.220
- I read about it in a magazine.
- Wow,

13:16.300 --> 13:18.820
Tiger Beat sure has changed from
when I was a little girl.

13:18.980 --> 13:20.420
I don't read Tiger Beat.

13:29.660 --> 13:33.300
Okay, Ruby, you want to try to tell me
everything you remember about the picture?

13:33.820 --> 13:37.860
All right. There were 3 kids
swinging on a tire swing.

13:38.020 --> 13:39.340
That's right.

13:40.020 --> 13:44.500
And there was 3 men jogging,
all with their left foot forward.

13:44.940 --> 13:46.380
That's very good.

13:46.700 --> 13:50.460
And one had a white baseball hat,

13:50.580 --> 13:52.820
and the other had a jacket.

13:55.700 --> 13:56.940
Anything  else?

13:57.140 --> 13:58.900
Do you want me to tell you everything?

13:59.420 --> 14:00.380
Hmm...

14:01.660 --> 14:02.700
Sure.

14:03.180 --> 14:04.140
Okay...

14:04.540 --> 14:08.780
There was someone
in the playground holding...

14:09.700 --> 14:11.460
3...  4 balloons,

14:12.100 --> 14:15.180
2 were red, 1 was orange,
and 1 was yellow.

14:15.300 --> 14:17.140
The orange one had the longest string.

14:17.300 --> 14:19.300
There's a place to play in the water,

14:19.980 --> 14:23.140
and these 3 boys who are way too
old be playing in the playground

14:24.100 --> 14:26.500
were standing in misty spray things,

14:26.740 --> 14:29.580
and these 2 little babies
were waiting for their turn.

14:29.900 --> 14:33.180
And in the sky
there were 2 clouds, 1 kite

14:33.300 --> 14:35.980
with 2 tails and...

14:37.820 --> 14:40.460
3 lamps with 2 lights each.

14:51.980 --> 14:54.660
- Hey.
- Okay, so we got the Galantamine,

14:54.860 --> 14:56.420
Accupril, Benazepril,

14:56.500 --> 14:58.300
Calan, Digitoxin, Lanoxin...

14:58.460 --> 15:00.900
- Herdofoxen.
- ... Xanax, Ritalin,

15:01.100 --> 15:02.540
Dilantin, Trimethadione,

15:02.700 --> 15:05.020
all the antibiotics,
manpower at all the other labs

15:05.140 --> 15:07.860
and a giant robotic arm
at Jarrell Pharmaceuticals.

15:09.300 --> 15:12.180
What's 11,291 times 16, divided by 7?

15:12.580 --> 15:14.780
25,808, why?

15:15.020 --> 15:18.460
- Did I miss something?
- No. I was just kidding.

15:20.860 --> 15:23.180
Okay Ruby, thank you very much.

15:23.380 --> 15:24.980
So I'm not gonna die?

15:25.740 --> 15:27.900
Ruby, you're not even sick.

15:28.380 --> 15:29.940
Then let's go home.

15:30.740 --> 15:33.500
- Where's your backpack?
- In my classroom.

15:33.540 --> 15:35.900
Why don't you go get it
and I'll meet you in the hall?

15:35.940 --> 15:38.100
- All right.
- See you later, Ruby.

15:38.220 --> 15:39.900
- Ciao, Ruby.
- Bye!

15:41.060 --> 15:42.860
- Can I ask you something?
- Please.

15:43.300 --> 15:46.980
Ruby ate all that
infected chicken last year

15:47.100 --> 15:50.220
and ever since
she's been poked and prodded...

15:50.660 --> 15:53.420
MRIs, blood tests, X-Rays.

15:54.860 --> 15:57.900
It's been 6 months and
no one has any answers.

15:59.140 --> 16:01.380
Well, it's just that right now,

16:01.500 --> 16:04.780
there's no way to tell for certain
whether someone exposed to prion disease

16:04.860 --> 16:06.780
actually has the disease.

16:07.340 --> 16:10.500
Ruby gets a runny nose, coughs...

16:10.780 --> 16:13.420
and I start thinking this is it,

16:13.580 --> 16:15.300
She's gonna die.

16:16.220 --> 16:17.780
We need answers,

16:17.900 --> 16:18.940
please.

16:49.580 --> 16:52.900
So, the drugs are doing their drug
thing, we'll check 'em in 12 hours.

16:53.060 --> 16:55.780
- How's it going with patient zero?
- Slow.

16:56.060 --> 16:57.700
Sean moved around a lot.

16:57.860 --> 17:01.100
It seems he met a lot of different people
in a lot of different places.

17:02.900 --> 17:04.300
How are you holding up?

17:04.859 --> 17:07.859
Okay. It's hard to sleep these days.

17:08.180 --> 17:10.420
You know they've got drugs for that.
In fact, Bob's got

17:10.540 --> 17:12.660
all of them over there.

17:15.859 --> 17:16.700
Goodnight.
- Okay.

17:19.900 --> 17:23.220
- Carlos.
- Wes, let me ask you something.

17:24.619 --> 17:25.980
Sean sent these 2 emails
in the last month.

17:26.140 --> 17:28.380
Does not say
where they were from.

17:28.540 --> 17:30.980
Is it possible to trace what
computer they were sent from?

17:31.140 --> 17:33.180
Sure, forensic email tracing.

17:33.460 --> 17:35.300
Well, this shouldn't be a problem
at all. What are you thinking?

17:35.380 --> 17:38.260
This girl is in 2 of the pictures.
One was sent late at night,

17:38.380 --> 17:40.460
the other very early
in the morning, and...

17:40.820 --> 17:42.620
Sean seems happy in them.

17:44.260 --> 17:45.580
She's very pretty.

17:46.260 --> 17:49.180
Just  a hunch, but if you
find something, let me know.

17:49.460 --> 17:50.340
Sure.

17:51.700 --> 17:53.180
Thank you.

18:00.940 --> 18:04.620
A quarter of the kids had
bloody amazing beta activity.

18:04.780 --> 18:06.060
Come see.

18:09.900 --> 18:11.140
Look at that.

18:11.300 --> 18:13.020
Tiny little hippocampuses,

18:13.140 --> 18:15.420
and dentate gyri firing away,
so cute.

18:15.620 --> 18:19.260
So it's not overall I.Q. that's higher,
it's visual memory.

18:19.340 --> 18:21.340
Right, yeah.
That's mostly where it's occurring.

18:21.460 --> 18:24.100
Okay, where is Ruby McGhee's PET output?

18:26.060 --> 18:27.260
Here.

18:28.380 --> 18:31.580
I mean, her right hemisphere
alone could power 5 city blocks.

18:31.780 --> 18:35.220
Your "live, die or thrive"
theory might need to be adjusted.

18:35.700 --> 18:38.500
It seems that with prion
poisoning some live,

18:38.620 --> 18:39.700
some die,

18:39.900 --> 18:43.020
and some become
bloody visual geniuses.

18:43.180 --> 18:44.780
Well, it's still early stages.

18:44.940 --> 18:46.460
Right, well, I mean,

18:47.900 --> 18:49.460
we're off to a great start.

18:55.020 --> 18:56.540
Uh, yeah. Well...

18:58.100 --> 19:00.980
Okay, I will see you tomorrow.

19:05.540 --> 19:06.940
All right.
Tomorrow, then.

19:22.140 --> 19:25.020
- It's not time.
- What? It's close enough.

19:26.140 --> 19:28.300
We have to let the drugs
work for 12 hours.

19:28.460 --> 19:30.940
Bob, it's been 12 hours minus what?
Ten big fat minutes?

19:30.980 --> 19:32.540
I'm checking the dishes.

19:33.060 --> 19:34.260
Wait.

19:59.580 --> 20:01.180
Are the viruses
thriving in the cells?

20:01.300 --> 20:02.620
Yeah, so far.

20:02.740 --> 20:04.780
Wait a sec. David. David, David, David.

20:04.900 --> 20:06.140
We have a winner.

20:06.500 --> 20:08.380
- It works, one of the cocktails.
- No shit?

20:08.580 --> 20:11.740
Yeah, none. It halts replication
of Audrey's HIV.

20:11.900 --> 20:14.900
A drug from a clinical trial
and a couple of existing HIV drugs.

20:15.020 --> 20:17.300
- This is a non-HIV drug.
- Freaking Paroxetine.

20:17.460 --> 20:19.100
And antidepressant, eh?

20:19.300 --> 20:21.420
How appropriate, I couldn't be happier.
Good work.

20:23.100 --> 20:26.300
I need you to wrangle me experts
on Tenofovir, PA-457,

20:26.460 --> 20:30.180
Viracept and Trimethadione. I also need
somebody here working on Paroxetine

20:30.260 --> 20:33.020
- and I need to speak to a hospital lawyer.
- Can I get you a coffee, too?

20:33.300 --> 20:35.940
No, you can get the cocktail
to Audrey for her 1st dosage

20:36.060 --> 20:38.580
and get me a meeting
with her son's pediatrician.

20:38.900 --> 20:40.620
Was that subtle sarcasm?

20:41.780 --> 20:42.660
No.

20:43.220 --> 20:44.460
Oh, too bad.

20:44.540 --> 20:46.980
Sarcasm would work well with
that bland exterior of yours.

21:08.940 --> 21:11.340
<i>- Yup.
- Hi, it's Mayko.</i>

21:16.460 --> 21:19.020
Uh... last year there were...

21:19.300 --> 21:21.380
542 students

21:21.500 --> 21:25.660
at Linderville Elementary,
and this year they've got 540.

21:27.580 --> 21:28.940
- Two lucky ones escaped.
- Well...

21:29.060 --> 21:32.100
actually 9 escaped and
7 new ones were captured, so...

